I finally borrowed a windows machine from someone and looked at this. It&#39;s
really fun to watch! I am leaving it running overnight to see what happens.
So far the best I have seen has been about a five mini-step shuffle
backwards...although I have seen a few three mini-step forward shuffles.

Can you post either the genome and or a movie of the best org you&#39;ve seen so
far? 

I second the notion that it would be cool to browse the archive, especially
if you could choose archive members to view based on max distance from 0,0
or something like that.

It might help you to visualize things if you added another viewing mode that
put a dot in the 3D viewer for every x,y,z coordinate in the archive (one
color) and in the current population (another color).

Watching this also makes me wonder about the population losing its gradient
and disengaging. Here is the potential concern (and I think mattias and ken
discussed this already): Once all the easy to access points are found, if
most of the orgs are not getting somewhere new, they will all have equal
fitnesses and the search will not be focused on the outside edge. Do you
think this is happening (and might this be why David mentioned that he saw a
lot of repeats toward the end)? The visualization I just proposed might help
on this front. Do the points added in the archive tend to be further and
further away from 0,0....or is it just filling in the spaces in the nearby
vicinity? 

Despite these concerns/suggestions, it is very fun stuff to look at...and
its exciting that you are hybridizing these ideas so quickly and testing
them. 


Cheers,
Jeff Clune

